Praveen,

Thanks for the reply.

I am aware of the use of TestSuite to limit test cases, but this won&#39;t 
work when test cases are run under the JUnit task in Ant, which uses its 
own TestSuite to reflectively include all methods for all classes found 
in its file list.  My JUnit task looks like this:

    &lt;junit printsummary=&quot;yes&quot; showoutput=&quot;no&quot; haltonerror=&quot;yes&quot; 
haltonfailure=&quot;no&quot;
           fork=&quot;yes&quot; jvm=&quot;${java.home}/bin/java.exe&quot;&gt;
      &lt;formatter type=&quot;plain&quot; usefile=&quot;false&quot;/&gt;
      &lt;formatter type=&quot;xml&quot;/&gt;
      &lt;batchtest todir=&quot;${unit.classes.dir}&quot;&gt;
        &lt;fileset dir=&quot;${unit.classes.dir}&quot;
              includes=&quot;
                  mypackage/myclass.class&quot;
              excludes=&quot;
                  *$*.class&quot;/&gt;
      &lt;/batchtest&gt;
      &lt;classpath refid=&quot;unit.tests.path&quot;/&gt;
    &lt;/junit&gt;

Whether the &quot;fileset&quot; task includes a class specifically or via 
wildcard, JUnit will instantiate a TestSuite, reflectively find all 
methods in a class that begin with &quot;test&quot;, and then attempt to execute 
them.  In our cases, there are a number of existing methods which begin 
with &quot;test&quot; but are protected and thus do not get executed.  However, 
this leads to test method failures.  Now, I could rename these methods 
to avoid the errors, but I am hoping to find a way around it so that 
developers in the future could add methods to future test classes 
without having to worry about not naming them test*.

Thanks again,

Shawn


